This is the first issue of beatochess.

I am currently going through the studies by Zakhodyakin in Harold van der Heijden’s HHdbVI database.

I am also looking at some older studies published in Shakhmatny Listok.

In this issue, you find a few comments, new cooks, and revisions.

EG 2023

Published in: EG July 2023.

File: Neuenschwander-2023-EG-233.pgn

GBR: =0000.33e1h6 FEN: 8/1p6/7k/p1p5/P7/P7/P7/4K3 w - - 0 1

1. Kd1 (Black has a strong passed pawn and a tempo in reserve, b7-b6. White has two resources. First, the position with wKd2 and bKd4, White draws by 1. Kc2 c3 2. Kb3 Kd3 stalemate, or 2….b5 3.Kc2 bxa4 3.Kd1 c2+ 4.Kc1 Kc3 stalemate. Second, White can steal Black’s tempo by moving the wK to c4, although White must then be careful not to lose the horizontal opposition. White draws by respecting the following corresponding squares (wK/bK with Black to move), depending on whether the black pawn is on b7 or b6. Corresponding squares with bPb7: d5/d3, e5/c2, f5/c4,b2,d2, g5/c4,c2, h5/c4,e4,b2,d2, d4/d2, e4/c3,e2, f4/b3,d3, g4/c3, h4/b3,d3. Corresponding squares with bPb6: e3/c3, f3/b3,d3, g3/c3,e3, h3/b3,d3,f3, e2/c2, f2/b2,d2, g2/c2,e2, h2/b2,d2,f2. In the following, all moves are only moves if not mentioned otherwise.) (1. Kd2? Kh5 2. Kd3 Kh4 3. Kc4 b6 4. Kb3 Kh3 5. Kb2 Kh2 6. Kc2 (6. Kc3 Kg1 (or Kg3) ) 6… Kg2) (1. Ke2? Kg5) (1. Kf2? Kh5) 1… Kg6 2. Kc1 (2. Kc2? Kg5) (2. Kd2? Kf5) (2. Ke2? Kg5) 2… Kg5 (2… Kf6 3. Kd1 (or Kb1) 3… Ke5 4. Kc2 Kd4 5. Kd2 c4 6. Kc2 c3 7. Kb3 b5 (7… Kd3 stalemate ) 8. Kc2 (8. axb5? Kd3) 8… bxa4 9. Kc1 Kd3 10. Kd1 c2+ 11. Kc1 Kc3 stalemate ) 3. Kc2 (3. Kb2? Kf5) (3. Kd2? Kf5) 3… Kg4 (3… Kf5 4. Kd2 (or Kb2) ) (3… Kf4 4. Kd3 (or Kb3) ) (3… Kh4 4. Kd3 (or Kb3) ) 4. Kc3 (4. Kd3? Kf4 (or Kh4) ) 4… Kg3 (4… Kf3 5. Kc4 b6 6. Kd3 (or Kb3) ) (4… Kh3 5. Kc4 b6 6.
